{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619104"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16538"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16538"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.05,0.11,0.68,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9229"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75408"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9229"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60918"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7146"},{"type":"tags","id":"8561"},{"type":"tags","id":"10338"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21875"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75408"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum contains distinct functional regions that contribute to balance and movement control. The vermis and flocculonodular lobe are particularly important for maintaining posture and equilibrium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following descending tracts is most directly influenced by the vermis and flocculonodular lobe of the cerebellum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rubrospinal tract","Anterior corticospinal tract","Reticulospinal tract","Vestibulospinal tract","Tectospinal tract"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum plays a crucial role in coordinating movement and balance through its influence on various descending motor pathways. The vestibulocerebellum (flocculonodular lobe) and vermis are particularly important in maintaining balance and postural control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibulospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E is most directly influenced by these cerebellar regions. This tract originates in the vestibular nuclei, which receive direct projections from the flocculonodular lobe. It is crucial for maintaining balance and posture, particularly in response to head movements and changes in body position.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erubrospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E originates in the red nucleus and is more influenced by the lateral cerebellar hemispheres rather than the vermis or flocculonodular lobe. It is involved in fine motor control of the limbs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior corticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E is a direct pathway from the motor cortex and is not significantly influenced by these cerebellar regions. It primarily controls voluntary movement of the axial and proximal limb muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the \u003Cstrong\u003Ereticulospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E does receive some input from the vermis, it is not as directly influenced as the vestibulospinal tract. It plays a role in postural control and automatic movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etectospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E originates in the superior colliculus and is primarily involved in head and neck movements in response to visual stimuli. It has minimal direct connection with these cerebellar regions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The vestibulocerebellum (flocculonodular lobe) primarily regulates balance and equilibrium through connections with vestibular nuclei.","The vermis influences axial and trunk muscle control through connections with vestibulospinal and reticulospinal tracts.","The cerebellum coordinates movement through its influence on descending motor pathways rather than direct motor control."],"references":["McCall AA, Miller DM, Yates BJ. Descending Influences on Vestibulospinal and Vestibulosympathetic Reflexes. Front Neurol. 2017 Mar 27;8:112. doi: 10.3389/fneur.2017.00112. PMID: 28396651; PMCID: PMC5366978.","Sullivan EV. Cognitive functions of the cerebellum. Neuropsychol Rev. 2010 Sep;20(3):227-8. doi: 10.1007/s11065-010-9144-8. Epub 2010 Sep 2. PMID: 20811946; PMCID: PMC4723423.","Gillig PM, Sanders RD. Psychiatry, neurology, and the role of the cerebellum. Psychiatry (Edgmont). 2010 Sep;7(9):38-43. PMID: 20941351; PMCID: PMC2952646.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60918"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16538"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60918"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T19:33:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T22:25:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9229"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75408"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"a